\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b1\i0\ul\ulc0 The First Half Of This Balance - Imagination, & The Nature And Location Of Computation}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \li720\ltrch\loch \ls2\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Using the imagination to "paste over" the difficulties of creating meaningful, character-led systems is nothing new - games rely heavily on psychological and imaginative impulses in their audience to augment their concrete representations. This is not a controversial or new stance. This has become a very important, fashionable stance. The \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93weak AI\u8221\'94 approach. Origins in Turing Test - \u8220\'93aesthetic illusion is therefore a transmedial, transmodal and transgeneric phenomenon\u8221\'94 - "an agent\u8217\'92s capacity to both enable and manage the adoption of the intentional stance in a player" - "predictable, contextual behavior is enough to trigger the intentional stance, through a process not dissimilar to narrative closure, and an information load that gives just enough to enable this process \endash  but no more"}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls2\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It is not novel to say that, like every type of artwork, the imagination, the autocosmics, of the audience is an important augmentative force in the resonance of the characters and narratives contained within it - even if we frame this as a different type of computation. This is not something which games and other computational artforms neglect - all of them realise, even in their technological utopianism, that }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93the}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 success of an AI-based artwork is based on audience perception". }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mention this exemplified in the perceived differences between \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91academic\u8217\'92 AI and \u8216\'91industry\u8217\'92 AI (Togelius and others), especially in the work on \u8216\'91non-platonic AI\u8217\'92 by Bungie in HALO and now copied by many others. }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93Tricks, arcane optimizations, and unproven techniologies\u8221\'94 -}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  since the early days of simpler characters. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Whereas computer simulations run on computers, literary simulations\u8230\'85 run on minds\u8221\'94 - So according to this theory the performance of a play or the text of a novel is a simulation just as a computer program can be a simulation; and in order to work the simulation must be run.\u8221\'94 - However, it has been debated whether humanlike internal processes are necessary at all, or whether the replication of surface displays is sufficient for a believable and effective communication. Kramer, Iurgel, and Bente (2005) argue that to reach the ultimate goal of an ECA \endash  to make the human\endash computer interaction more intuitive and to manipulate the emotions of the user \endash  it is not necessary to simulate internal processes in terms of an emotion model or motivation model. Instead they propose a conversational function model where emotional expressions are seen as purely instrumental and disconnected from the feeling of emotions (cf. Fridlund, 1991) - Companion cube}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93When you are designing a game you are not designing just a set of rules, but a set of rules that will always be experienced as play within a cultural context\u8230\'85 you never have the luxury of forgetting about context\u8221\'94}
