\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls2\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Talk about Oatley here - \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93the mind\u8217\'92s flight simulator\u8221\'94, fiction \u8220\'93offer[s] us cues to our theory-of-mind processes\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93get the whole thing to run\u8221\'94 - his view of mimesis as simulation, \u8220\'93run on the minds of the audience, as a computer simulation runs on a computer\u8221\'94, novels and plays \u8220\'93guide the simulation process\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93Literary simulations run on minds of audiences or readers, just as computer simulations run on computers.\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls2\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Only, it may be that humanity\u8217\'92s capacity for living in empirical and virtual worlds at once is not a late-twentieth century development, even if current technology brings this characteristic into sharper relief. It may be that varieties of theater and games of all sorts have always been helping us into the place away from the lives that nature forces on us, where the worlds we imagine are possible.\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93A stirring narrative in any medium can be experienced as a virtual reality\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}\f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls2\ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs24\b1\i0	\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f1\fs24\b1\i0 The many ways that games and other computational artworks have courted and used the \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8216\'91aesthetic illusion\u8217\'92 AND \u8220\'93non-aesthetic illusion\u8221\'94 of the audience, especially with characters }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 - \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93reflective choices\u8221\'94 or \u8220\'93the illusion of choice\u8221\'94 (Anthropy & Clark) in games (The Walking Dead) - If you look for choice, you are \u8216\'91robbing yourself of the illusion\u8217\'92 \u8220\'93Power over plot seems limited\u8221\'94 - ontological geek - Games like The Wolf Among Us have their ma- jor plot points laid out and will follow through with their progression no matter what the player does - but there are still plenty of options given to her. Their purpose is to re- flect on the events of the story rather than to lead them. In this perspective, "The actor\u8217\'92s reasons for taking their actions are predetermined by the author to lend believability to their behaviours"(Thue, Bulitko, & Spetch, 2008). (Stadeler) - Abbott and many other fans find her even more compelling than a character in a work of fiction, because players of the game are responsible for her survival.(BUT NOT REALLY!) - , the \u8220\'93representational and narrative power\u8221\'94 of the computer with ELIZA and PARRY through the \u8220\'93intentional stance\u8221\'94 (re. H&S - Talk about parasites as tribute to heider and simmels experiment, now called \u8216\'91The ELIZA Effect\u8217\'92 - - "attributing greater intelligence or intentionality to a machine than it possesses"  Braitenberg Vehicles (Emmeche)) - }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93Weizenbaum had set out to make a clever computer program and had unwittingly created a believable character\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 (Murray), }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93maintains the illusion\u8230\'85 with very little machinery\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 commented on by Thomas Was Alone - }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93love how such simple shapes can form such strong personalities\u8230\'85 found myself imagining little conversations between them as I played.\u8220\'93}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  (Stephen O\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92Donnell) - in study, gendering characters, switching between first and third person depending on control, even though he said \u8220\'93\u8220\'93If these two can even be called characters\u8221\'94 or \u8220\'93ridiculous\u8221\'94 to say that they had personalities - naming him, telling him to \u8220\'93come on, Thomas/you\u8221\'94, compares them to a friend\u8217\'92s ex-boyfriend or their friends with the same name,, gives them personality traits such as \u8220\'93innocent\u8221\'94, \u8220\'93pessimistic\u8221\'94, \u8220\'93rude\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s not just a block\u8221\'94. Even felt like the narration was paying attention to what she did! Thomas\u8217\'92 dark soul was alone says that we don\u8217\'92t really need the narrator, could turn the sound off. "I found myself describing the game avatars as if they were social others without cognizantly recognizing I was doing so. " "Looking at things pragmatically, the role of the team is to build a system that shows signs of intelligence. "The best strategy for that is to find the right balance between human supervision and technology." - \u8220\'93Ideally you want to borrow the intelligence of the designers to make the AI seem smart, but you want to use the generalization of code to make the intelligence procedural (you can\u8217\'92t ship a designer on a CD).\u8221\'94}
